This paper focuses on the optimization of activation functions in deep neural networks, which is a topic closely related to neural network architecture and optimization. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Additionally, the paper proposes the use of genetic algorithms to learn the best activation function, which falls under the category of machine learning and optimization, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The paper also evaluates the performance of the proposed activation functions on image classification benchmarks, which falls under the category of computer vision, making cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) a likely sub-category. Furthermore, the paper discusses the importance of activation functions in general, which is a topic related to artificial intelligence, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a framework for optimizing activation functions, which can be seen as a system-level approach to neural network optimization, making cs.SY (Systems and Control) a possible sub-category as well.
